<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-677-644  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 677 644.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Software  July 1990 v7 n4 p82(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Create the best first impression. (Human Factors)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Potosnak, Kathleen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The user interface aspects of installation, customization,configuration, troubleshooting procedures, and customer supportoften get little time or attention from the software companydeveloping the product.andP;  But if users cannot install a product,they cannot use it.andP;  Most installation and customizationprocedures require users to know too much about computing.andP;  Thereare ways companies can make their software products better andeasier to use: make installation easy, do not require users toknow everything there is to know about their computers if theprogram can find it out for them, include explanations in thesoftware of what it is supposed to do, have updates automaticallyremove unneeded code, make minimum system requirements clear,provide a way for users to reconfigure their systems easily, letusers customize features, but make it easy to return to defaultsettings; include easy-to-follow troubleshooting procedures, withtips built into the software; track support, supply an onlinebulletin board for users to communicate with each other, includedata collection modules in the software and test for usability.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Human FactorsSoftware EngineeringSoftware PackagesUser Interface.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>